content.description: Awesome.  A couple big moves over several stacked small boulders allow you to reach the Yosemite style dihedral.  The crack begins with perfect hand jams and slowly widens towards the top.  You wont want to come off this one up high!
content.protection: Several pads and spotters would allow it to be bouldered more safely.  Also, the dihedral would be easily protectable on lead via cams of various sizes.
content.location: High in the canyon, just before the rocky staircase section of trail with the guard rail.  Immediately to the right of the trail (hikers right while moving away from the trailhead).

content.description: Great highball problem.  Subtle face moves up excellent rock.  Flat landing but the encroaching Manzanita does not allow room for either a pad or a spotter.  Respect the vegetation and either do it old-shool with no pad and no spot or leave it alone for now.
content.location: Straight up the obvious face just left of Lieback Frannie.

content.description: Climb the section or rock directly above the "20" carving.  Sit start is maybe V2.
content.location: Hike to the Mcmenemy Trail turn off.  Head down the Mcmenemy Trail several feet.  The 20 Bag boulder can be seen just a couple feet off the trail to the hikers left.

content.description: Great dynamic moves up the obvious arete.
content.location: Immediately right of the trail, just before the first of the switchbacks high in the canyon.

content.description: Will be great after it cleans up some from some traffic.  Starts back in the cave, moves qcross the lip and then reachy moves get you out and over for the  topout.
content.location: From on top of the Good Medicine boulders, the Scatter Gun boulders lie directly uphill and represent the right-most of the nearest rocks.

content.description: Grab the shelf, then make big moves off insecure features up the steep face.  Highball.
content.location: After the Wet Work area, look for the huge split boulder down and left of the trail.  Scramble down and around it.  The Oracle faces the creek.  El Mugroso is to the right.

content.description:
Rock simply does not get better than this. In SB or anywhere, as far as Im concerned.

A mantle gains the tall, black, low angle face. Follow easy moves to the top.
content.location: About halfway between Lower San Ysidro and the Wet Work Dihedral area, look down towards the creek for the obvious huge boulder, with the awesome black face, sitting in the water.

content.description: A series of cool lieback moves around a roof.  A good spot to learn about cam placement.  Somewhat contrived for a boulder problem though; the climber can easily step off onto a cheater stone at any point.
content.location: The second line of boulders above Weeny Roofs. Or head to the topout of Face Lift then go around or over the boulders immediately above.

content.description: Blunt arete onn the boulder to the right of Scatter Gun.
Hug the imposing needle of rock such that one feels a real possibility of damage to the crotch region.
content.location: To the  left of Scatter Gun.

content.description: The steeper, right hand side of the 20 Bag boulder.  Sit start goes at about V2.
content.location: Hike to the Mcmenemy Trail turn off.  Head down the Mcmenemy Trail several feet.  The 20 Bag boulder can be seen just a couple feet off the trail to the hikers left.

content.description: Reach high to good holds and pull/campus so as to reach to obvious flake.  Climb up and right to the top.
content.location: Take the Mcmenemy Trail, one half mile from the car, pass the 20 Bag boulder and cross the creek. Just past the creek look up and right for the boulder perched among the eucalyptus.  The problem, "The Euc's" climbs the obvious flake on the side facing the trail.

content.description: Easy moves up this beautiful face lead to two slightly-larger-than-fist sized huecos.  Grab these two big jugs (sorry....) and head straight for the top.
content.location: San Ysidro, Lower (Topside Bouldering).  On the far-side of the next cluster uphill from the Scatter Gun Boulders.

content.description: Can be done as a single move, or a couple harder moves.  Sit start off the best holds you can reach and huck for the top, or bump your way up via the mono on the right.
content.location: On the side of the "Euc" boulder, to the right of The Euc's.

content.description: The left most of the three 20 Bag problems.  Low angle, but deceptively "sequencey" moves head straight up.
content.location: The first boulder encountered once the dirt road properly begins.  Where the Mcmenemy Trail (Lower) meets the dirt road, .5 miles from the trailhead parking, the top of the 20 bag boulder can be see.  Head down the Mcmenemy trail a few feet and the 20 Bag problems can be seen on the hikers left. The 20 Bag boulder can be identified by noting the "20" chiseled into the rock face.
